# UI Kit: gluestack-ui

This project uses **[gluestack-ui](https://gluestack.io/ui/docs)** as the default UI kit. All new UI must be built on it.

## Rules

- Prefer gluestack primitives (`Box`, `VStack`, `HStack`, `Text`, `Heading`, `Button`, `Card`, `Badge`, `Input`, `Pressable`, `Skeleton`, `GlassView`, etc.) over raw React Native `View`/`Text`/`Pressable` for layout and chrome.
- Import kit primitives from `@/components/ui/<component>` (CLI-generated lowercase folders).
- Import Fine AI composed wrappers from `@/components/patterns/*` (Button, Card, Badge, ThemedText, EmptyState, etc.).
- Keep the Fine AI theme (`src/theme/tokens.ts` + `global.css`). Do not invent a new palette.
- Style with UniWind `className` aligned to theme tokens (`bg-background`, `text-foreground`, `bg-primary`, etc.).
- If a component does not exist in gluestack, compose it from kit primitives first; only then add custom RN/layout code.
- App-specific shells (`AppShell`, `FloatingNavbar`, `StatusBadge`) live in `src/components/` and **must** use gluestack as the base.
- Floating glass / blur chrome uses gluestack **Liquid Glass** (`GlassView` / `GlassContainer` from `@/components/ui/liquid-glass`), with blur fallback when liquid glass is unavailable.
- Do not introduce another UI library (NativeBase, Tamagui, Paper, etc.) without an explicit decision.

## Adding kit pieces

```bash
npx gluestack-ui@latest add <component-name>
```

Docs: https://gluestack.io/ui/docs
